𝗜𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗹𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗹𝘆 𝗸𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗣𝗜 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲? 🐌➡️🚀Using Serilog to write logs directly to the Console or a File? While this is a common pattern, often shown in initial examples and tutorials, it might be 'wrong'—or at least, seriously suboptimal—for your API's performance.Ever deployed your .NET API, hit your endpoints, and been shocked by response times like 150ms, 200ms, or even more? You check your code, your database calls, everything seems fine... but it's sluggish. 🤯The culprit could be hiding in plain sight: 𝗦𝘆𝗻𝗰𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗟𝗼𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴When you configure Serilog sinks like .WriteTo.Console() or .WriteTo.File() directly, each log message often blocks your request thread until the write operation completes. In a busy API, this adds up fast, tanking your performance.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗙𝗶𝘅? 𝗚𝗼 𝗔𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗰!The solution is incredibly simple: wrap your sinks with Serilog.Sinks.Async. This moves the actual I/O work to a background thread, freeing up your API threads almost instantly.𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗲! 👇 It shows the simple NuGet package to install and the configuration change you need to make. It's usually just a matter of adding .Async(a => ...) around your existing sink configurations.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁: Those 200ms endpoints can plummet to 2-5ms. Night and day difference!Don't let synchronous logging be your performance bottleneck. Check your Serilog setup and make the switch to async sinks – see the image for how easy it is!Have you hit this wall before? 𝗜𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗹𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗹𝘆 𝗸𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗣𝗜 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲? 🐌➡️🚀Using Serilog to write logs directly to the Console or a File? While this is a common pattern, often shown in initial examples and tutorials, it might be 'wrong'—or at least, seriously suboptimal—for your API's performance.Ever deployed your .NET API, hit your endpoints, and been shocked by response times like 150ms, 200ms, or even more? You check your code, your database calls, everything seems fine... but it's sluggish. 🤯The culprit could be hiding in plain sight: 𝗦𝘆𝗻𝗰𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗟𝗼𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴When you configure Serilog sinks like .WriteTo.Console() or .WriteTo.File() directly, each log message often blocks your request thread until the write operation completes. In a busy API, this adds up fast, tanking your performance.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗙𝗶𝘅? 𝗚𝗼 𝗔𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗰!The solution is incredibly simple: wrap your sinks with Serilog.Sinks.Async. This moves the actual I/O work to a background thread, freeing up your API threads almost instantly.𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗲! 👇 It shows the simple NuGet package to install and the configuration change you need to make. It's usually just a matter of adding .Async(a => ...) around your existing sink configurations.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁: Those 200ms endpoints can plummet to 2-5ms. Night and day difference!Don't let synchronous logging be your performance bottleneck. Check your Serilog setup and make the switch to async sinks – see the image for how easy it is!Have you hit this wall before? 𝗜𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗹𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗹𝘆 𝗸𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗣𝗜 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲? 🐌➡️🚀Using Serilog to write logs directly to the Console or a File? While this is a common pattern, often shown in initial examples and tutorials, it might be 'wrong'—or at least, seriously suboptimal—for your API's performance.Ever deployed your .NET API, hit your endpoints, and been shocked by response times like 150ms, 200ms, or even more? You check your code, your database calls, everything seems fine... but it's sluggish. 🤯The culprit could be hiding in plain sight: 𝗦𝘆𝗻𝗰𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗟𝗼𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴When you configure Serilog sinks like .WriteTo.Console() or .WriteTo.File() directly, each log message often blocks your request thread until the write operation completes. In a busy API, this adds up fast, tanking your performance.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗙𝗶𝘅? 𝗚𝗼 𝗔𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗰!The solution is incredibly simple: wrap your sinks with Serilog.Sinks.Async. This moves the actual I/O work to a background thread, freeing up your API threads almost instantly.𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗲! 👇 It shows the simple NuGet package to install and the configuration change you need to make. It's usually just a matter of adding .Async(a => ...) around your existing sink configurations.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁: Those 200ms endpoints can plummet to 2-5ms. Night and day difference!Don't let synchronous logging be your performance bottleneck. Check your Serilog setup and make the switch to async sinks – see the image for how easy it is!Have you hit this wall before? 𝗜𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗹𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗹𝘆 𝗸𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗣𝗜 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲? 🐌➡️🚀Using Serilog to write logs directly to the Console or a File? While this is a common pattern, often shown in initial examples and tutorials, it might be 'wrong'—or at least, seriously suboptimal—for your API's performance.Ever deployed your .NET API, hit your endpoints, and been shocked by response times like 150ms, 200ms, or even more? You check your code, your database calls, everything seems fine... but it's sluggish. 🤯The culprit could be hiding in plain sight: 𝗦𝘆𝗻𝗰𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗟𝗼𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴When you configure Serilog sinks like .WriteTo.Console() or .WriteTo.File() directly, each log message often blocks your request thread until the write operation completes. In a busy API, this adds up fast, tanking your performance.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗙𝗶𝘅? 𝗚𝗼 𝗔𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗰!The solution is incredibly simple: wrap your sinks with Serilog.Sinks.Async. This moves the actual I/O work to a background thread, freeing up your API threads almost instantly.𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗲! 👇 It shows the simple NuGet package to install and the configuration change you need to make. It's usually just a matter of adding .Async(a => ...) around your existing sink configurations.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁: Those 200ms endpoints can plummet to 2-5ms. Night and day difference!Don't let synchronous logging be your performance bottleneck. Check your Serilog setup and make the switch to async sinks – see the image for how easy it is!Have you hit this wall before? 𝗜𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗹𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗹𝘆 𝗸𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗣𝗜 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲? 🐌➡️🚀Using Serilog to write logs directly to the Console or a File? While this is a common pattern, often shown in initial examples and tutorials, it might be 'wrong'—or at least, seriously suboptimal—for your API's performance.Ever deployed your .NET API, hit your endpoints, and been shocked by response times like 150ms, 200ms, or even more? You check your code, your database calls, everything seems fine... but it's sluggish. 🤯The culprit could be hiding in plain sight: 𝗦𝘆𝗻𝗰𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗟𝗼𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴When you configure Serilog sinks like .WriteTo.Console() or .WriteTo.File() directly, each log message often blocks your request thread until the write operation completes. In a busy API, this adds up fast, tanking your performance.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗙𝗶𝘅? 𝗚𝗼 𝗔𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗰!The solution is incredibly simple: wrap your sinks with Serilog.Sinks.Async. This moves the actual I/O work to a background thread, freeing up your API threads almost instantly.𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗲! 👇 It shows the simple NuGet package to install and the configuration change you need to make. It's usually just a matter of adding .Async(a => ...) around your existing sink configurations.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁: Those 200ms endpoints can plummet to 2-5ms. Night and day difference!Don't let synchronous logging be your performance bottleneck. Check your Serilog setup and make the switch to async sinks – see the image for how easy it is!Have you hit this wall before? 𝗜𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗹𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗹𝘆 𝗸𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗣𝗜 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲? 🐌➡️🚀Using Serilog to write logs directly to the Console or a File? While this is a common pattern, often shown in initial examples and tutorials, it might be 'wrong'—or at least, seriously suboptimal—for your API's performance.Ever deployed your .NET API, hit your endpoints, and been shocked by response times like 150ms, 200ms, or even more? You check your code, your database calls, everything seems fine... but it's sluggish. 🤯The culprit could be hiding in plain sight: 𝗦𝘆𝗻𝗰𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗟𝗼𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴When you configure Serilog sinks like .WriteTo.Console() or .WriteTo.File() directly, each log message often blocks your request thread until the write operation completes. In a busy API, this adds up fast, tanking your performance.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗙𝗶𝘅? 𝗚𝗼 𝗔𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗰!The solution is incredibly simple: wrap your sinks with Serilog.Sinks.Async. This moves the actual I/O work to a background thread, freeing up your API threads almost instantly.𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗲! 👇 It shows the simple NuGet package to install and the configuration change you need to make. It's usually just a matter of adding .Async(a => ...) around your existing sink configurations.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁: Those 200ms endpoints can plummet to 2-5ms. Night and day difference!Don't let synchronous logging be your performance bottleneck. Check your Serilog setup and make the switch to async sinks – see the image for how easy it is!Have you hit this wall before? 𝗜𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗹𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗹𝘆 𝗸𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗣𝗜 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲? 🐌➡️🚀Using Serilog to write logs directly to the Console or a File? While this is a common pattern, often shown in initial examples and tutorials, it might be 'wrong'—or at least, seriously suboptimal—for your API's performance.Ever deployed your .NET API, hit your endpoints, and been shocked by response times like 150ms, 200ms, or even more? You check your code, your database calls, everything seems fine... but it's sluggish. 🤯The culprit could be hiding in plain sight: 𝗦𝘆𝗻𝗰𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗟𝗼𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴When you configure Serilog sinks like .WriteTo.Console() or .WriteTo.File() directly, each log message often blocks your request thread until the write operation completes. In a busy API, this adds up fast, tanking your performance.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗙𝗶𝘅? 𝗚𝗼 𝗔𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗰!The solution is incredibly simple: wrap your sinks with Serilog.Sinks.Async. This moves the actual I/O work to a background thread, freeing up your API threads almost instantly.𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗲! 👇 It shows the simple NuGet package to install and the configuration change you need to make. It's usually just a matter of adding .Async(a => ...) around your existing sink configurations.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁: Those 200ms endpoints can plummet to 2-5ms. Night and day difference!Don't let synchronous logging be your performance bottleneck. Check your Serilog setup and make the switch to async sinks – see the image for how easy it is!Have you hit this wall before? 𝗜𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗹𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗹𝘆 𝗸𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗣𝗜 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲? 🐌➡️🚀Using Serilog to write logs directly to the Console or a File? While this is a common pattern, often shown in initial examples and tutorials, it might be 'wrong'—or at least, seriously suboptimal—for your API's performance.Ever deployed your .NET API, hit your endpoints, and been shocked by response times like 150ms, 200ms, or even more? You check your code, your database calls, everything seems fine... but it's sluggish. 🤯The culprit could be hiding in plain sight: 𝗦𝘆𝗻𝗰𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗟𝗼𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴When you configure Serilog sinks like .WriteTo.Console() or .WriteTo.File() directly, each log message often blocks your request thread until the write operation completes. In a busy API, this adds up fast, tanking your performance.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗙𝗶𝘅? 𝗚𝗼 𝗔𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗰!The solution is incredibly simple: wrap your sinks with Serilog.Sinks.Async. This moves the actual I/O work to a background thread, freeing up your API threads almost instantly.𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗲! 👇 It shows the simple NuGet package to install and the configuration change you need to make. It's usually just a matter of adding .Async(a => ...) around your existing sink configurations.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁: Those 200ms endpoints can plummet to 2-5ms. Night and day difference!Don't let synchronous logging be your performance bottleneck. Check your Serilog setup and make the switch to async sinks – see the image for how easy it is!Have you hit this wall before? 𝗜𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗹𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗹𝘆 𝗸𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗣𝗜 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲? 🐌➡️🚀Using Serilog to write logs directly to the Console or a File? While this is a common pattern, often shown in initial examples and tutorials, it might be 'wrong'—or at least, seriously suboptimal—for your API's performance.Ever deployed your .NET API, hit your endpoints, and been shocked by response times like 150ms, 200ms, or even more? You check your code, your database calls, everything seems fine... but it's sluggish. 🤯The culprit could be hiding in plain sight: 𝗦𝘆𝗻𝗰𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗟𝗼𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴When you configure Serilog sinks like .WriteTo.Console() or .WriteTo.File() directly, each log message often blocks your request thread until the write operation completes. In a busy API, this adds up fast, tanking your performance.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗙𝗶𝘅? 𝗚𝗼 𝗔𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗰!The solution is incredibly simple: wrap your sinks with Serilog.Sinks.Async. This moves the actual I/O work to a background thread, freeing up your API threads almost instantly.𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗲! 👇 It shows the simple NuGet package to install and the configuration change you need to make. It's usually just a matter of adding .Async(a => ...) around your existing sink configurations.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁: Those 200ms endpoints can plummet to 2-5ms. Night and day difference!Don't let synchronous logging be your performance bottleneck. Check your Serilog setup and make the switch to async sinks – see the image for how easy it is!Have you hit this wall before? 𝗜𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗹𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗹𝘆 𝗸𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗣𝗜 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲? 🐌➡️🚀Using Serilog to write logs directly to the Console or a File? While this is a common pattern, often shown in initial examples and tutorials, it might be 'wrong'—or at least, seriously suboptimal—for your API's performance.Ever deployed your .NET API, hit your endpoints, and been shocked by response times like 150ms, 200ms, or even more? You check your code, your database calls, everything seems fine... but it's sluggish. 🤯The culprit could be hiding in plain sight: 𝗦𝘆𝗻𝗰𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗟𝗼𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴When you configure Serilog sinks like .WriteTo.Console() or .WriteTo.File() directly, each log message often blocks your request thread until the write operation completes. In a busy API, this adds up fast, tanking your performance.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗙𝗶𝘅? 𝗚𝗼 𝗔𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗰!The solution is incredibly simple: wrap your sinks with Serilog.Sinks.Async. This moves the actual I/O work to a background thread, freeing up your API threads almost instantly.𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗲! 👇 It shows the simple NuGet package to install and the configuration change you need to make. It's usually just a matter of adding .Async(a => ...) around your existing sink configurations.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁: Those 200ms endpoints can plummet to 2-5ms. Night and day difference!Don't let synchronous logging be your performance bottleneck. Check your Serilog setup and make the switch to async sinks – see the image for how easy it is!Have you hit this wall before? 𝗜𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗹𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗹𝘆 𝗸𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗣𝗜 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲? 🐌➡️🚀Using Serilog to write logs directly to the Console or a File? While this is a common pattern, often shown in initial examples and tutorials, it might be 'wrong'—or at least, seriously suboptimal—for your API's performance.Ever deployed your .NET API, hit your endpoints, and been shocked by response times like 150ms, 200ms, or even more? You check your code, your database calls, everything seems fine... but it's sluggish. 🤯The culprit could be hiding in plain sight: 𝗦𝘆𝗻𝗰𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗟𝗼𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴When you configure Serilog sinks like .WriteTo.Console() or .WriteTo.File() directly, each log message often blocks your request thread until the write operation completes. In a busy API, this adds up fast, tanking your performance.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗙𝗶𝘅? 𝗚𝗼 𝗔𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗰!The solution is incredibly simple: wrap your sinks with Serilog.Sinks.Async. This moves the actual I/O work to a background thread, freeing up your API threads almost instantly.𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗲! 👇 It shows the simple NuGet package to install and the configuration change you need to make. It's usually just a matter of adding .Async(a => ...) around your existing sink configurations.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁: Those 200ms endpoints can plummet to 2-5ms. Night and day difference!Don't let synchronous logging be your performance bottleneck. Check your Serilog setup and make the switch to async sinks – see the image for how easy it is!Have you hit this wall before? 𝗜𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗹𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗹𝘆 𝗸𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗣𝗜 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲? 🐌➡️🚀Using Serilog to write logs directly to the Console or a File? While this is a common pattern, often shown in initial examples and tutorials, it might be 'wrong'—or at least, seriously suboptimal—for your API's performance.Ever deployed your .NET API, hit your endpoints, and been shocked by response times like 150ms, 200ms, or even more? You check your code, your database calls, everything seems fine... but it's sluggish. 🤯The culprit could be hiding in plain sight: 𝗦𝘆𝗻𝗰𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗟𝗼𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴When you configure Serilog sinks like .WriteTo.Console() or .WriteTo.File() directly, each log message often blocks your request thread until the write operation completes. In a busy API, this adds up fast, tanking your performance.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗙𝗶𝘅? 𝗚𝗼 𝗔𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗰!The solution is incredibly simple: wrap your sinks with Serilog.Sinks.Async. This moves the actual I/O work to a background thread, freeing up your API threads almost instantly.𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗲! 👇 It shows the simple NuGet package to install and the configuration change you need to make. It's usually just a matter of adding .Async(a => ...) around your existing sink configurations.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁: Those 200ms endpoints can plummet to 2-5ms. Night and day difference!Don't let synchronous logging be your performance bottleneck. Check your Serilog setup and make the switch to async sinks – see the image for how easy it is!Have you hit this wall before? 𝗜𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗹𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗹𝘆 𝗸𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗣𝗜 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲? 🐌➡️🚀Using Serilog to write logs directly to the Console or a File? While this is a common pattern, often shown in initial examples and tutorials, it might be 'wrong'—or at least, seriously suboptimal—for your API's performance.Ever deployed your .NET API, hit your endpoints, and been shocked by response times like 150ms, 200ms, or even more? You check your code, your database calls, everything seems fine... but it's sluggish. 🤯The culprit could be hiding in plain sight: 𝗦𝘆𝗻𝗰𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗟𝗼𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴When you configure Serilog sinks like .WriteTo.Console() or .WriteTo.File() directly, each log message often blocks your request thread until the write operation completes. In a busy API, this adds up fast, tanking your performance.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗙𝗶𝘅? 𝗚𝗼 𝗔𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗰!The solution is incredibly simple: wrap your sinks with Serilog.Sinks.Async. This moves the actual I/O work to a background thread, freeing up your API threads almost instantly.𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗲! 👇 It shows the simple NuGet package to install and the configuration change you need to make. It's usually just a matter of adding .Async(a => ...) around your existing sink configurations.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁: Those 200ms endpoints can plummet to 2-5ms. Night and day difference!Don't let synchronous logging be your performance bottleneck. Check your Serilog setup and make the switch to async sinks – see the image for how easy it is!Have you hit this wall before? 𝗜𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗹𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗹𝘆 𝗸𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗣𝗜 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲? 🐌➡️🚀Using Serilog to write logs directly to the Console or a File? While this is a common pattern, often shown in initial examples and tutorials, it might be 'wrong'—or at least, seriously suboptimal—for your API's performance.Ever deployed your .NET API, hit your endpoints, and been shocked by response times like 150ms, 200ms, or even more? You check your code, your database calls, everything seems fine... but it's sluggish. 🤯The culprit could be hiding in plain sight: 𝗦𝘆𝗻𝗰𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗟𝗼𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴When you configure Serilog sinks like .WriteTo.Console() or .WriteTo.File() directly, each log message often blocks your request thread until the write operation completes. In a busy API, this adds up fast, tanking your performance.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗙𝗶𝘅? 𝗚𝗼 𝗔𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗰!The solution is incredibly simple: wrap your sinks with Serilog.Sinks.Async. This moves the actual I/O work to a background thread, freeing up your API threads almost instantly.𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗲! 👇 It shows the simple NuGet package to install and the configuration change you need to make. It's usually just a matter of adding .Async(a => ...) around your existing sink configurations.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁: Those 200ms endpoints can plummet to 2-5ms. Night and day difference!Don't let synchronous logging be your performance bottleneck. Check your Serilog setup and make the switch to async sinks – see the image for how easy it is!Have you hit this wall before? 𝗜𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗹𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗹𝘆 𝗸𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗣𝗜 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲? 🐌➡️🚀Using Serilog to write logs directly to the Console or a File? While this is a common pattern, often shown in initial examples and tutorials, it might be 'wrong'—or at least, seriously suboptimal—for your API's performance.Ever deployed your .NET API, hit your endpoints, and been shocked by response times like 150ms, 200ms, or even more? You check your code, your database calls, everything seems fine... but it's sluggish. 🤯The culprit could be hiding in plain sight: 𝗦𝘆𝗻𝗰𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗟𝗼𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴When you configure Serilog sinks like .WriteTo.Console() or .WriteTo.File() directly, each log message often blocks your request thread until the write operation completes. In a busy API, this adds up fast, tanking your performance.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗙𝗶𝘅? 𝗚𝗼 𝗔𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗰!The solution is incredibly simple: wrap your sinks with Serilog.Sinks.Async. This moves the actual I/O work to a background thread, freeing up your API threads almost instantly.𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗲! 👇 It shows the simple NuGet package to install and the configuration change you need to make. It's usually just a matter of adding .Async(a => ...) around your existing sink configurations.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁: Those 200ms endpoints can plummet to 2-5ms. Night and day difference!Don't let synchronous logging be your performance bottleneck. Check your Serilog setup and make the switch to async sinks – see the image for how easy it is!Have you hit this wall before? 𝗜𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗹𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗹𝘆 𝗸𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗣𝗜 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲? 🐌➡️🚀Using Serilog to write logs directly to the Console or a File? While this is a common pattern, often shown in initial examples and tutorials, it might be 'wrong'—or at least, seriously suboptimal—for your API's performance.Ever deployed your .NET API, hit your endpoints, and been shocked by response times like 150ms, 200ms, or even more? You check your code, your database calls, everything seems fine... but it's sluggish. 🤯The culprit could be hiding in plain sight: 𝗦𝘆𝗻𝗰𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗟𝗼𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴When you configure Serilog sinks like .WriteTo.Console() or .WriteTo.File() directly, each log message often blocks your request thread until the write operation completes. In a busy API, this adds up fast, tanking your performance.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗙𝗶𝘅? 𝗚𝗼 𝗔𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗰!The solution is incredibly simple: wrap your sinks with Serilog.Sinks.Async. This moves the actual I/O work to a background thread, freeing up your API threads almost instantly.𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗲! 👇 It shows the simple NuGet package to install and the configuration change you need to make. It's usually just a matter of adding .Async(a => ...) around your existing sink configurations.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁: Those 200ms endpoints can plummet to 2-5ms. Night and day difference!Don't let synchronous logging be your performance bottleneck. Check your Serilog setup and make the switch to async sinks – see the image for how easy it is!Have you hit this wall before? 𝗜𝘀 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗹𝗼𝗴 𝘀𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗹𝘆 𝗸𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗣𝗜 𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲? 🐌➡️🚀Using Serilog to write logs directly to the Console or a File? While this is a common pattern, often shown in initial examples and tutorials, it might be 'wrong'—or at least, seriously suboptimal—for your API's performance.Ever deployed your .NET API, hit your endpoints, and been shocked by response times like 150ms, 200ms, or even more? You check your code, your database calls, everything seems fine... but it's sluggish. 🤯The culprit could be hiding in plain sight: 𝗦𝘆𝗻𝗰𝗵𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗟𝗼𝗴𝗴𝗶𝗻𝗴When you configure Serilog sinks like .WriteTo.Console() or .WriteTo.File() directly, each log message often blocks your request thread until the write operation completes. In a busy API, this adds up fast, tanking your performance.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗙𝗶𝘅? 𝗚𝗼 𝗔𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗰!The solution is incredibly simple: wrap your sinks with Serilog.Sinks.Async. This moves the actual I/O work to a background thread, freeing up your API threads almost instantly.𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗲! 👇 It shows the simple NuGet package to install and the configuration change you need to make. It's usually just a matter of adding .Async(a => ...) around your existing sink configurations.𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘂𝗹𝘁: Those 200ms endpoints can plummet to 2-5ms. Night and day difference!Don't let synchronous logging be your performance bottleneck. Check your Serilog setup and make the switch to async sinks – see the image for how easy it is!Have you hit this wall before?
